{
  "text": "The major findings of the present study are that chronic or acute administration of the selective D 3 R antagonist YQA14 significantly inhibits the acquisition and expression of METHinduced locomotor sensitization and the expression of METHinduced CPP in a dose-dependent manner. In addition, the chronic administration of YQA14 also facilitates the extinction of reward-seeking and attenuates the METH-induced reinstatement of CPP. These data suggest that brain D [CITATION_1] Rs play a critical role in the stimulatory effects of METH. Thus, YQA14 or other D 3 R antagonists warrant further research aimed at studying their effect as potential pharmacotherapies for METH addiction.",
